<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="233" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,638,1496,1518]" box="[151,638,1496,1518]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
<typeStatus box="[151,201,1497,1518]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName box="[293,376,1496,1518]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Makrostyles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terrifica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[293,376,1496,1518]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">terrifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[382,463,1497,1518]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, here designated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1437,1563,1984]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[274,410,1563,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Makrostyles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[274,410,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Makrostyles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here established to classify another species from 
<collectingCountry box="[994,1117,1563,1588]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
with the 
<taxonomicName authority="Felt, 1908" authorityName="Felt" authorityYear="1908" box="[1223,1385,1563,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Johnsonomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1223,1385,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Johnsonomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like general appearance combined with presence of highly unusual male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="233" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1437,1563,1984]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1635,1660]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Most notably, the gonostylus of 
<taxonomicName box="[707,843,1635,1660]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Makrostyles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[707,843,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Makrostyles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is equipped with an excessively large apical tooth, which is strongly bent in the proximal half and slightly angled subapically (↓, 
<figureCitation box="[1095,1203,1671,1696]" captionStart="FIGURE 17 A – C" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1946,1968]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,887,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,878,1924]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 17 A – C. Makrostyles terrifica, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Wing (paratype). C: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (paratype). Scales for A, C, 0.05 mm, for B, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267039/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
Fig. 
<number box="[1152,1180,1672,1696]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" value="17.0">17</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). The teeth of both gonostyli cross each other at exactly the point of the subapical angle. The copulatory organ is peculiar for its elaborate structure, including a convex, subtrapezoid ventral shield and a dorsal pair of finger-like, largely separated, microtrichose processes arising from a common sclerotized base (↓, 
<figureCitation box="[1032,1136,1779,1804]" captionStart="FIGURE 17 A – C" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1946,1968]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,887,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,878,1924]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 17 A – C. Makrostyles terrifica, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Wing (paratype). C: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (paratype). Scales for A, C, 0.05 mm, for B, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267039/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
Fig. 
<number box="[1083,1112,1780,1804]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" value="17.0">17</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). The ejaculatory apodeme is not traceable as a discrete structure, but might be incorporated in the copulatory organ. The massive gonocoxae, which are much broader than long, have greatly developed, protruding medial bridges and unusually small dorsal apodemes (
<figureCitation box="[278,382,1887,1912]" captionStart="FIGURE 17 A – C" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1946,1968]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,887,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,878,1924]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 17 A – C. Makrostyles terrifica, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Wing (paratype). C: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (paratype). Scales for A, C, 0.05 mm, for B, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267039/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
Fig. 
<number box="[331,359,1888,1912]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233" value="17.0">17</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[532,668,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Makrostyles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[532,668,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Makrostyles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="233" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1437,1563,1984]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1923,1948]" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is composed of the Greek words 
<emphasis box="[973,1054,1923,1948]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">makros</emphasis>
, for large, and 
<emphasis box="[1247,1311,1923,1948]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="233">stylos</emphasis>
, for style, meaning “with large gonostyli”. Gender of the name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
